
CODEX SKILLS
============

DIRECTORY STRUCTURE:
   skill-name/
      SKILL.md     (req - instructions + routing)
      scripts/     (executable actions)
      references/  (domain knowledge)
      templates/   (output patterns)
      config/      (defaults - no secrets)
      fixtures/    (test examples)
      schemas/     (structured formats)
      docs/        (human reference)

LOCATION:
   repo/.codex/skills/  (project local)
   ~/.codex/skills/    (user global)
   /etc/codex/skills/   (system wide)

### Skill Discovery Rules

Directory contains → `SKILL.md`
Front matter includes → name + description
Description → routing signal

SKILL.md STRUCTURE:
---
name: skill-name
description: When to use skill
---

When to use
Inputs required
Safety rules
Execution instructions

SCRIPTS
Purpose:
Execute work
Call APIs
Transform data
Run tools

<BREAK>

SCRIPT NAMES:
   object-verb
   mail-send
   git-pr-review
   security-audit

SCRIPT FOLDER NAME:
   ≈ skill identity**

SKILLS ARE TRIGGERED:
   Match based on:
      * User request intent
      * SKILL.md description
      * Explicit naming

ADVANCED SKILL DESIGN
   * Clear use conditions
   * Required input checklist
   * Safety / confirmation rules
   * Exact execution commands
   * Error handling guidance
   Never store:
      API keys, Passwords, Tokens
   Use: env, external config

Codex can:
   * Generate skill skeleton
   * Write SKILL.md
   * Create scripts

You can also use:
   * skill-creator tools
   * skill installer workflows

Good Skill Traits
   Deterministic behavior
   Clear scope boundaries
   Minimal hidden assumptions
   Script-backed execution
   Explicit confirmation rules
   Input validation

EOF
) | awk -F'\t' '{ printf "%-50s  %s\n", $1, $2 }'
